So your task is to replace the aging Flock framework with a JesseQ-based implementation while maintaining the goals of MPCAuth, you should transition from a hybridSPDZ/AGMPC architecture to a Vector-OLE (VOLE) based Designated-Verifier Zero-Knowledge (DV-ZKP) architecture.Recommended Library StackFor a modern equivalent that leverages JesseQ, the following library combination is the most optimal for your performance goals:Core Protocol (JesseQ): MengLing-L/JesseQWhy: This is the specific implementation of the 2025 optimization of QuickSilver. It is built on top of the emp-toolkit stack you are already using in the current mpcauth code, making the migration path more straightforward.Cryptographic Backend: emp-toolkit/emp-zkWhy: JesseQ requires the underlying VOLE and commitment primitives provided by emp-zk. This replaces the older emp-agmpc library used in your current repository.TLS Support: wolfSSLWhy: You should still use wolfSSL. The MPCAuth framework explicitly uses wolfSSL because it allows for the "handshake key revelation" optimization, which is essential to prevent TLS timeouts when Establish a connection in SMPC. Most standard libraries (like OpenSSL) do not provide the low-level hooks needed to perform the handshake derivation within an external MPC engine efficiently.Modifying the SMTP ServerTo integrate this with an SMTP server for authenticated passcodes, you do not necessarily need to modify the server itself if you use the TLS-in-SMPC approach described in the MPCAuth paper.Implementation Strategy: Your $N$ servers act as a single "logical" SMTP client using the JesseQ-optimized TLS pipeline.The "Motherfuckers" (SMTP Intermediaries): Instead of modifying a standard server like Postfix or Exim, you should use an SMTP Gateway pattern.The $N$ servers jointly generate the passcode and use JesseQ to prove the encryption of the SMTP payload.One server (the "forwarder") sends the JesseQ-proven, TLS-encrypted packet to a standard SMTP provider (like Gmail or AWS SES).Because you are revealing the handshake keys but keeping the application keys (the passcode body) hidden, the external SMTP server will see a valid, standard TLS connection and accept the mail without knowing the content.Summary RecommendationLibrary: Use the JesseQ repository as your primary engine.Dependencies: Keep wolfSSL for the TLS state machine and emp-zk for the backend.SMTP: Do not modify the SMTP server; instead, use the Gateway Optimization where $N$ servers establish a JesseQ-hardened TLS session to a standard provider.

