Having logical components and flow flow 1. Enrollment: sharding the addressWhen you first register, your client application (which runs locally on your device and is the only entity that knows your email) performs the following steps:Secret Sharing: The app takes your email address and breaks it into $N$ mathematical "shares" (shards).Distribution: The app establishes a separate TLS connection to each of the $N$ servers and sends only one shard to each server.Privacy: Because the email is secret-shared, an individual server only holds a piece of "gibberish" that cannot be used to reconstruct your email address unless all $N$ servers (or a threshold) collude.2. Authentication: The "TLS-in-SMPC" TunnelWhen the servers need to send you a passcode, they use a process that keeps the email hidden even while it is being used to route the message:Joint Assembly: The servers use Secure Multi-Party Computation (SMPC) to "assemble" the email address inside a protected cryptographic environment.Encrypted Hand-off: Inside that same SMPC environment, they run the TLS protocol to encrypt the email content and the "To:" field.Gateway Forwarding: One of the servers (the forwarder) sends the resulting encrypted packets to a standard email provider like Gmail.The Provider's Role: The email provider (the "motherfucker" in the middle) is the only external entity that sees the plaintext email address so it can deliver the message to your inbox.3. Identity AssociationThe servers identify you not by your email, but by a unique identifier (like a chosen username) that you provide during enrollment.This username acts as the index for your account.The servers map this username to the specific shards of your profile (email, phone number, or biometrics) that they hold locally.When you want to authenticate, you tell the servers your username, and they pull their respective shards to begin the joint TLS process.


To visualize how MPCAuth functions as a "blend" of servers communicating with a regular mail provider, the architecture can be broken down into three distinct logical layers: the Client, the MPC Cluster, and the Unmodified Infrastructure.Logical Nodes and Data FlowClient Application (User Device)Function: Acts as the user interface.Enrollment: Shards sensitive data (like your email address) into $N$ mathematical shares and sends exactly one to each server node.Authentication: Receives the passcode from your inbox and sends a proof (PRF) of that passcode to the individual servers.MPC Cluster (The 5 Servers)Function: These are $N$ nodes (e.g., 5 servers) hosted in different trust domains.Joint Operations: They use JesseQ or QuickSilver to perform bitwise logic (AES, SHA-256) without any single server seeing the plaintext.The "Logical Client": Together, they behave as one single, virtual TLS client.Handshake Revelation Node: They use wolfSSL to reveal "handshake keys" so they can verify the external mail server's identity quickly without timing out.Forwarder Node (One of the 5 Servers)Function: This specific node is designated to handle the physical network connection (TCP/IP) to the outside world.Data Integrity: It forwards the JesseQ-proven, TLS-encrypted packets to the mail gateway. It cannot alter the content because the other nodes would detect a proof failure.External Mail Gateway (e.g., Google/Gmail)Function: A standard, unmodified SMTP server.Visibility: It receives what looks like a perfectly normal TLS-encrypted email from a single source. It is the only entity that sees the plaintext "To:" address to deliver the passcode to your inbox.The Interaction DiagramPlaintext[ USER APP ] 
